<section xml:id="activity-rational-functions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
 <title>Rational Functions</title>
  <objectives>
   <title>Student Learning Outcomes</title>
    <introduction>
     <p>After completing this activity you will be able to:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ol>
     <li>
      <p>
       Determine the domain, range, intercepts, holes, end behavior, vertical and horizontal asymptotes (if they exist) of a rational function.
      </p>
     </li>
     <li>
      <p>
       Create a graph by hand and on the calculator of a rational function (given in factored form).
      </p>
     </li>
    </ol>
   </objectives>
 <subsection>
  <title>What is a Rational Function?</title>
    <p>Basically, a <term>rational funciton</term><idx><h>rational funciton</h></idx> is a fraction. It is composed of a numerator and a denominator in which both are polynomials. For instance, all of the functions listed below are rational functions.</p>
    <example>
      <p>
       <ul>
        <li>
         <p><m>\frac{x^{2}-5x}{10-3x^{3}+22x^{7}}</m></p>
        </li>
        <li>
         <p><m>\frac{4}{x}</m></p>
        </li>
        <li>
         <p><m>\frac{100x^{10}-x}{x+1}</m></p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      </p>
    </example>
  </subsection>
</section>
